  "prompt": "Do candles spoil?",
  "response": "Candles don't spoil in the traditional sense like food does, but they can degrade over time. Here are some factors to consider:\n\n1. **Wax Quality**: Over time, the quality of the wax can break down, especially if exposed to fluctuating temperatures. This can affect the burn quality and scent throw of the candle.\n\n2. **Wick Condition**: The wick can become brittle or discolored if stored for a long time, which might make it harder to light or cause it to burn unevenly.\n\n3. **Scent**: Fragrance oils in scented candles can evaporate or degrade, leading to a diminished scent over time.\n\n4. **Color**: Colored candles might fade if exposed to sunlight.\n\n5. **Storage**: Proper storage can extend the life of a candle. Keep them in a cool, dark place, away from direct sunlight and extreme temperatures.\n\nWhile candles don't have an expiration date, using them within a reasonable time frame (typically a few years) will ensure the best performance. If you notice any unusual changes in appearance, smell, or burn quality, it might be time to replace the candle.",
